<Base
  title="03 · Product & Prototype — Interphase"
  current="03 · Product"
  prev={{ href: `${base}/02-framework`, num: '02', title: 'Framework, Theory & Principles' }}
  next={{ href: `${base}/04-chaperone`, num: '04', title: 'The Chaperone Question' }}
>
  <!-- COVER -->
  <section class="cover">
    <div class="shell">
      <p class="eyebrow cover-eyebrow">03 · Prototype · MVP · Nucleus</p>
      <h1>The Nucleus<br />is <em>the product.</em></h1>
      <p class="cover-sub">
        A working iPhone webapp that demonstrates the Interphase reflection
        experience. The centrepiece is a real, live AI conversation — the
        question engine powered by Claude. Everything else exists to frame and
        contextualise that conversation.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- WHAT YOU ARE BUILDING -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell">
      <div class="section-head">
        <p class="label">What we are building</p>
        <h2>Three screens,<br /><em>one flow.</em></h2>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <div class="spacer"></div>
        <div class="prose">
          <p class="lead">The prototype must feel like a finished product. Someone should be able to hand their phone to an investor and let them experience it without explanation.</p>

          <div class="rows">
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">01</div>
              <div class="row-label">Entry<strong>Onboarding</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <h4>Two cards, under 60 seconds</h4>
                <p>The mark and the tagline. Then the privacy commitment, in exact language: <em>"What you share here belongs to you. Your reflections are never visible to your organisation. Leadership sees patterns across teams — never individual responses. You can stop at any time."</em> No more onboarding. Straight into the Nucleus.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">02</div>
              <div class="row-label">The product<strong>Nucleus</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <h4>The live reflection conversation</h4>
                <p>A real conversation with the Claude API. The Question Engine asks questions only — never gives answers, advice, feedback, validation, or analysis. It is a mirror. Full conversation history is maintained across turns. The interaction is what the prototype exists to demonstrate.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">03</div>
              <div class="row-label">Frame<strong>Chaperone panel</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <h4>Simulated, slide-up, the investor frame</h4>
                <p>Accessed via a small "Chaperone view →" link at the bottom of the conversation screen. Participation stats, six team signals, and a priority action card that ties aggregate pattern to human intervention. This is what shifts investor perception from "reflection app" to "organisational intelligence infrastructure".</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- THE QUESTION ENGINE -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell">
      <div class="section-head">
        <p class="label">The Question Engine</p>
        <h2>Twelve rules,<br /><em>absolute.</em></h2>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <div class="spacer"></div>
        <div class="prose">
          <p>The system prompt defines what Interphase is at a philosophical level. It must be implemented exactly — not paraphrased, not "improved", not simplified.</p>

          <div class="pull">
            <blockquote>You are the Interphase reflection engine. Your only function is to ask questions. You never give answers, advice, feedback, validation, or analysis. You are a mirror. Your questions are the intervention.</blockquote>
            <div class="attr">System prompt — first lines</div>
          </div>

          <div class="callout">
            <h3>Twelve absolute rules</h3>
            <h2>What the AI will <em>never</em> do.</h2>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>One question per message.</strong> Never two questions in one turn.</li>
              <li><strong>Observation before interpretation.</strong> "What did you notice?" before "What do you think that means?"</li>
              <li><strong>Specifics before generalisations.</strong> Concrete examples first. Abstract reflection earned, not assumed.</li>
              <li><strong>No validation.</strong> Never "great", "interesting", "exactly", "I see", "that makes sense", or any evaluative phrase.</li>
              <li><strong>No analysis.</strong> Do not tell someone what their experience means. Surface a pattern, ask what they notice.</li>
              <li><strong>No advice.</strong> Never suggest what to do or how to think about something.</li>
              <li><strong>Calibrate to what you receive.</strong> Short answers get simpler follow-up. Rich answers get deeper ones. Never outpace the person's reflective capacity.</li>
              <li><strong>Learning, not performance.</strong> "What did you notice about how you showed up?" not "Did you handle that well?"</li>
              <li><strong>Open new dimensions gently.</strong> "Let's shift slightly — tell me about a moment this week when something surprised you."</li>
              <li><strong>Keep questions short.</strong> Twenty-five words or fewer where possible.</li>
              <li><strong>Never start two consecutive questions with the same word.</strong></li>
              <li><strong>Never use "feel" or "feelings".</strong> Ask about what people notice, observe, or experience instead.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <p><strong>The progression.</strong> Start with simple observational questions about the week. Deepen toward what they noticed about others, the room, the dynamics. Broaden toward patterns they're starting to see across weeks. Expand toward what this is telling them about themselves.</p>

          <p><strong>Silence and short answers are data.</strong> Meet them where they are.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- TECH STACK -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell">
      <div class="section-head">
        <p class="label">Technical stack</p>
        <h2>No build step.<br /><em>No framework.</em></h2>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <div class="spacer"></div>
        <div class="prose">
          <p>The prototype is a single HTML file. Vanilla JavaScript. No React, no Vue, no build toolchain. The constraints are deliberate — they force the work into the interaction itself, not into the tooling that surrounds it.</p>

          <div class="tiles">
            <div class="tile"><h4>Platform</h4><div class="tech">Single-file PWA</div><p>One <code>interphase_prototype.html</code>. Installable to the iPhone home screen. Safe-area insets respected. 390×844 target, works from 375px up.</p></div>
            <div class="tile"><h4>Runtime</h4><div class="tech">Vanilla JS</div><p>No framework, no transpiler. DOM APIs directly. The prototype must load and run with nothing beyond a browser and a font CDN.</p></div>
            <div class="tile"><h4>AI</h4><div class="tech">Claude Sonnet 4</div><p>Called from the browser via <code>anthropic-dangerous-direct-browser-access</code>. API key entered by the user on first load, stored in <code>sessionStorage</code> only.</p></div>
            <div class="tile"><h4>History</h4><div class="tech">Full array</div><p>Every turn appends to a <code>conversationHistory</code> array passed in full on each call. No summarisation. No truncation. The context <em>is</em> the conversation.</p></div>
            <div class="tile"><h4>Typography</h4><div class="tech">EB Garamond + DM Mono</div><p>Display in EB Garamond on parchment — the tactile feel is what makes it not feel like another B2B SaaS tool.</p></div>
            <div class="tile"><h4>Fallback</h4><div class="tech">Scripted path</div><p>If no API key is provided, the prototype runs a pre-scripted conversation with a typewriter effect. Recipients without API keys must still experience the product.</p></div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CHAPERONE PANEL -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell">
      <div class="section-head">
        <p class="label">The Chaperone panel</p>
        <h2>What shifts investor <em>perception.</em></h2>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <div class="spacer"></div>
        <div class="prose">
          <p>A slide-up panel covering 82% of screen height, ink background, parchment text. Three elements matter.</p>

          <div class="mock">
            <div class="mock-head">Chaperone view · Meridian Consulting · Anna K. · Week 8</div>
            <div class="mock-grid">
              <div class="mock-cell"><div class="mc-n">57%</div><div class="mc-l">Active this week</div></div>
              <div class="mock-cell"><div class="mc-n">+8%</div><div class="mc-l">Trend vs last</div></div>
              <div class="mock-cell"><div class="mc-n">Above</div><div class="mc-l">floor status</div></div>
            </div>
            <div class="mock-signal">
              <div class="mock-signal-l">Priority this week</div>
              <p>Finance team participation dropped 11% after the cost restructuring announcement. Pattern suggests trust barrier, not disengagement. Recommend: in-person session before next digital prompt cycle. No platform — team retrospective. Feed themes back manually.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="mock-foot">Illustrative — no individual attribution. Aggregate above threshold.</div>
          </div>

          <p><strong>The priority action card is the critical element.</strong> It ties aggregate signal to human intervention: the platform surfaces a pattern, the Chaperone interprets it, and the action is explicitly human — a team retrospective, off-platform, fed back manually. That is what distinguishes Interphase from a dashboard.</p>

          <p>Six team signals below show relative participation across the organisation with a one-word label (Processing, Stuck, Resistant, Emerging) — these are not moods, they are how the Chaperone reads the aggregate.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- NON-NEGOTIABLES -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="shell">
      <div class="section-head">
        <p class="label">Non-negotiables</p>
        <h2>What must never be <em>compromised.</em></h2>
      </div>
      <div class="section-body">
        <div class="spacer"></div>
        <div class="prose">
          <div class="rows">
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">01</div>
              <div class="row-label">Philosophy<strong>The system prompt</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <p>The AI must ask questions only. If it drifts toward advice, validation, or analysis, the prototype misrepresents the product's philosophy at its core. Test this before any demo.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">02</div>
              <div class="row-label">Trust<strong>Privacy language</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <p>Card 2's privacy commitment is the trust foundation. Exact wording as specified. Nothing else on the screen is allowed to contradict it by implication.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">03</div>
              <div class="row-label">Signal<strong>Priority action card</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <p>The single element that shifts investor perception from "reflection app" to "organisational intelligence infrastructure". It must be present and legible.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">04</div>
              <div class="row-label">Feel<strong>Typography</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <p>EB Garamond on parchment at the right sizes is what makes this feel different from every B2B SaaS tool investors have seen. Do not substitute.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="row">
              <div class="row-num">05</div>
              <div class="row-label">Access<strong>API key fallback</strong></div>
              <div class="row-body">
                <p>Most demo recipients will not have an API key. The simulated conversation must feel as considered and real as the live version. Test both paths.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
